byline.contributor: Andrew Jacobs reported from Beijing, and Neil Gough from Hong Kong. Chris Buckley contributed reporting from Hong Kong, and Patrick Zuo contributed research from Beijing.
byline.original: By ANDREW JACOBS and NEIL GOUGH

abstract: Chinese Prime Min Li Keqiang outlines series of policies aimed at reaching economic growth rate of 7 percent and creating private sector jobs while weaning country off dependence on government employment; warns that country needs to overcome inefficiencies and barriers to private enterprise to achieve goal.
lead_paragraph: Prime Minister Li Keqiang lowered the country’s yearly target for economic growth and announced efforts to reduce China’s dependence on government-led infrastructure investment, heavy industry and low-end exports.

headline.main: Chinese Premier Sketches a Lofty Vision for Private Enterprise but Warns of Obstacles
headline.print_headline: Chinese Premier Warns of Economic Barriers to Private Enterprise
